What’s the HYPE with Hyperliquid?

Sunny Shi

22 minutes ago ⋅  17 min read

Key Insights

  • Hyperliquid’s growing L1 and planned EVM integration means comparisons to other perp DEXs are now too limiting.
  • We believe an ecosystem built around Hyperliquid’s composable order book can represent a new DeFi primitive.
  • The bull case for Hyperliquid’s perp DEX and EVM integration is that it can become a fully onchain version of Binance and BNB.
  • One of the best methods to gain exposure to Hyperliquid’s growth before the launch of its token is to look for investable opportunities in its underpenetrated spot market.
  • The market may be too conservative on Hyperliquid’s upside based on the OTC value of Hyperliquid points. Our valuation range portrays a wide spread of reasonable outcomes that could lead to points being worth between $10 and $30.

Introduction

Hyperliquid has been steadily expanding its products and use cases since it launched in late 2022. Over the past few months market participants have noticed consistently impressive onchain metrics, an ongoing points program, and new developments such as a burgeoning spot market and incoming third party protocols. The OTC value of Hyperliquid points have trended upwards, and as of writing is sitting at ~$5 a point.

With rapidly evolving capabilities, Hyperliquid now has a narrative problem. It wasn’t until April of this year that the protocol demonstrated it can offer more than just a decentralized perpetual exchange (perp DEX). Furthermore, due to the Arbitrum routed bridge, many still hold misconceptions that Hyperliquid is either an L3 or an app on the Arbitrum Layer-2. It is likely that there is an ongoing re-evaluation of the protocol by the market as they try to contextualize the new Hyperliquid story. This ultimately begs the question of what Hyperliquid’s narrative actually is.

In this report, we offer the characterization that Hyperliquid is a full-fledged Layer-1 that represents a new DeFi primitive in crypto. We prefer comparing Hyperliquid to an onchain Binance, rather than to other L1s. We will start with an explanation of the Hyperliquid L1, followed by a discussion on its differences compared to its crypto competitors and its similarities to Binance. Finally, we will analyze the different ways to gain exposure to Hyperliquid which will include a method for valuing points.

Explaining the Hyperliquid Layer-1

Hyperliquid was founded with the directive to build a fully onchain central-limit order book (CLOB) perp DEX whose performance could rival centralized exchanges (CEXs) like Binance. The team consists of ex high-frequency traders who see limitations in current onchain offerings but recognize the value of a fully transparent open-source alternative to CEXs after witnessing the collapse of FTX.

Why a Layer-1?

In order to deliver on a perp DEX that could rival the speed and UX of CEXs, Hyperliquid developed a highly performant L1 from the ground up. The L1 leverages a Proof-of-Stake (PoS) model and Hyperliquid’s own HyperBFT consensus algorithm in order to ensure low latency and high throughput. It is also configured end-to-end for high frequency order book trading, and is not designed to be a general purpose blockchain.

Why does Hyperliquid’s perp DEX require its own L1? Put simply:

  • High Frequency Trading (HFT) profits are limited if there are other general purpose transactions occupying demand for block space and competing for gas (in contrast, Hyperliquid’s trading experience is gasless; gas is only induced for transactions that increase state bloat i.e. spot listings or transferring to new wallets).
  • The chain must allow for specific order prioritization - such as for cancels and post-only limit orders which insure market makers aren’t subjected to as much toxic flow.

In addition, a CLOB exchange built for HFT requires strict control over specific mechanics, which is better enabled by a tailor-made solution that can optimize for them. These mechanics include:

  • Liquidating positions atomically based on the latest oracle price feed.
  • Strictly distributing funding payments in a single atomic operation consistently each hour.
  • Verifying solvency on the platform at the end of each block.

While other L1s and L2s can accomplish these capabilities, an optimized L1 can guarantee them more precisely without having to deal with network congestion.

Lastly, relying on out-of-the-box solutions such as Cosmos SDK and Tendermint (like its perp DEX competitor dYdX) can limit scalability, performance and configurability.

After transitioning from Tendermint consensus to Hyperliquid’s own solution, the chain saw a significant uptick in throughput as, unlike Ethereum and Tendermint, HyperBFT can continue sequencing transactions in parallel even while the hash of the current block has yet to be executed.

According to Hyperliquid’s docs, the mainnet currently offers sub-second latency even in the 99th percentile. It also supports 100 thousand orders/sec, which can continue to scale if the execution end is optimized. While these numbers are certainly impressive for an onchain offering, latency on a decentralized network will probably never match the full capabilities offered by a CEX. For example, the Nasdaq is able to optimize its latency down to nanoseconds. However, sub-second latency provides enough of a “CEX-like” experience for most crypto traders.

Centralization Concerns - A Work in Progress

While the L1 has been built for performance, there are some concerns around the network’s level of centralization. Currently, validator nodes are run by the team to reduce validation driven network latency and to facilitate frequent updates. Validators also perform other critical functions besides just producing blocks. These functions include securing the bridge and publishing prices on Hyperliquid’s native oracle to compute funding rates. It will be important for these processes to become more decentralized in the future. This has sparked some questions on how Hyperliquid plans to address this going forward.

As the first step in the decentralization process, Hyperliquid has recently rolled out non-validator (read-only) nodes which doesn’t actively participate in consensus but allows nodes not owned by the team to provide oversight and to audit full nodes. However, if the vision is to onboard sizable DeFi TVL, some potential users of the network would require larger scale decentralization efforts. The team has highlighted decentralization as a longer-term goal, and it will be more pertinent after development velocity slows down.

Hyperliquid as a New Primitive

Now that we have established that Hyperliquid is a performant Layer-1 and not just a perp DEX, we can help crystallize Hyperliquid’s narrative and identify its place within a growing landscape of competitors.

Hyperliquid vs dYdX

Let’s first address comparisons made to Hyperliquid’s main decentralized CLOB perp DEX competitor - dYdX.

Fully Onchain - It Matters

The key point of differentiation between Hyperliquid and dYdX v4 is that Hyperliquid has opted to build its order book and matching engine fully onchain. Having offchain operations means users are still unable to see what is happening on the order book / matching engine, which doesn’t provide a meaningful long-term alternative to CEXs. This is because:

  • It is impossible to verify whether any frontrunning is occurring without a mechanism in place to confirm that orders are following a strict time order ruleset. For example, it was reported that Alameda was likely frontrunning FTX users on token listings.
  • There is no oversight into whether order flow is being redirected. For example, Robinhood has often engaged in Payments for Order Flow (PFOF) behavior (selling order flow to market makers), failing to give users best execution on orders.

On the other hand, Hyperliquid’s onchain order book is the most transparent open source CLOB perp DEX at scale, and is built to protect the end user indefinitely. Crypto’s permissionless and trustless qualities are its edge, and Hyperliquid plans to deliver on those distinctions.

There are some notable trade-offs. Offchain order books require less validation which helps facilitate higher throughput and latency, but an end-to-end optimized tech stack like the one Hyperliquid employs helps mitigate any performance gaps (Hyperliquid’s metrics are already higher than or on par with dYdX v3’s). This does require more effort to build and iterate on the consensus algorithm, but the team at Hyperliquid has already worked through most of the up-front labor.

Secondly, sophisticated market makers may sometimes prefer a more “white-glove” market making experience which offchain order books can offer, but given Hyperliquid’s high quality order flow, liquidity is not in short supply.

The Hyperliquid Ecosystem is Moving Faster

When compared to dYdX, Hyperliquid is further along the curve of becoming an ecosystem of apps and products. The launch of its spot market and its planned EVM integration is moving the L1 towards becoming a full-fledged network that can offer more than just a perp DEX.

Hyperliquid vs Performant L1s and Parallelized EVMs

Hyperliquid’s L1 can also be compared to existing performant L1s like Solana. Subsequently, after Hyperliquid’s announcement in May that it will be working on integrating a native EVM, one could also liken the network to parallelized EVM chains like Monad and Sei Network.

Incoming support for EVM is an interesting point of differentiation to non-EVM performant L1s like Solana, and encourages greater interoperability with the rest of the EVM universe while delivering familiar tooling to attract EVM ready developers.

In comparison to other parallelized EVMs, Hyperliquid has already managed to build a killer crypto application in its perp DEX which has markedly outcompeted SEI in terms of attracting TVL. At this point, Hyperliquid has a product and a community, and is working on building out the rest of the ecosystem. Inversely, newer parallelized EVM networks are still looking for sticky applications and users.

Lastly, a major differentiator between Hyperliquid and these competitors is the network’s composability with a leading onchain order book. As the order book continues to win share, it becomes a larger moat.

The Hyperliquid Flywheel

Here are some examples of how the unique proximity to a composable order book and its related items can yield a host of innovative native DeFi applications which can now be built with EVM tooling:

  • Ethena-like protocols can utilize the native perp DEX to hedge exposure to volatile collateral instead of having to rely on offchain CEXs.
  • Options protocols built on Hyperliquid can utilize Hyperliquid’s native perp assets to create advanced trading strategies.
  • Lending protocols can use the native oracle to value collateral, then execute liquidations in Hyperliquid’s spot market. This reduces the need for protocols to access cross-platform oracles and liquidation markets, which can improve latency, cut complexity and offer more accurate liquidation pricing for native Hyperliquid spot collateral.
  • Other types of trading platforms (such as prediction markets or synthetics platforms) can tap into Hyperliquid’s order book for price discovery and lean on HyperBFT consensus for the settlement and distribution of funds in a timely manner.

The viability of these applications is strengthened by the continued share capture of Hyperliquid’s order book which drives high quality order flow and ample liquidity.

This creates a strong flywheel for Hyperliquid’s ecosystem:

The L1 is also optimized for trading, which accentuates the value proposition for related DeFi protocols to build on Hyperliquid over other alternatives like Solana and Monad. Lastly, Hyperliquid’s trading and DeFi oriented community is an accessible source of user acquisition for new teams interested in attracting that cohort.

A New Narrative - Onchain Binance

To summarize, Hyperliquid is not a blank slate general purpose L1. We believe Hyperliquid is building a new primitive, as its combination of unique onchain offerings can create a platform for novel configurations in DeFi that are more performant, efficient, and transparent.

Therefore, Hyperliquid is much more akin to a fully onchain and permissionless Binance than it is to other decentralized networks. Similarities include the fact that CZ also had a background in high-frequency trading before starting Binance, which started off as an exchange before expanding to include its own EVM-compatible BNB chain.

How to Capitalize

The final section of the report will highlight Hyperliquid’s potential upside, and how one could gain exposure.

Hyperliquid’s Growth Opportunity

Hyperliquid has generated impressive trading volume relative to other onchain perp DEXs. Its market share has expanded dramatically over the past year to overtake dYdX as crypto’s leading perp DEX by volume.

Despite this, there is a tremendous amount of white space before it reaches Binance’s level of trading activity. Hyperliquid’s perp volume represented only ~6% of that of the total Binance exchange in June. This leaves ample room for penetration as users who move onchain look for an onchain solution.

Can Hyperliquid Retain its Activity?

Unlike failed points implementations in the past, Hyperliquid has a much higher probability of retaining its onchain metrics and token price action post TGE. This is because:

  • The current weekly points distribution rubric is constantly changing and highly opaque, which creates a difficult environment for single-minded farmers to operate. Since the team has given almost nothing away on how points are rewarded, there is no farming “meta”. For example, there is speculation from users that the weighting of distributions between perps and spot is constantly changing and even within spot, it is rumored that factors like hold time and price action impact the distribution scale. These shifting benchmarks obfuscate the ability to rely on bot wallets and wash trading strategies. Additionally, dilution has reduced farming ROI. Because of these reasons, it is likely that those only concerned with farming have already tapped out, and current participants are largely made up of genuine users or Hyperliquid faithfuls.
  • A great case study for assessing Hyperliquid’s non-incentivized activity occurred in the month of May when the points program was halted. Despite some dropoff versus the preceding months, Hyperliquid’s volume as a percentage of Binance’s stayed relatively stable (indicating that the dropoff was largely macro-driven).
  • Oftentimes post TGE sell-offs occur when the community feels unsatisfied with their allocation or vesting restrictions (see EIGEN and BLAST). However, the Hyperliquid team has remained closed to private investors and contributors and are largely self-funded. The team also runs lean, with less than 10 total contributors. We believe the community allocation and its vesting flexibility will be markedly more favorable than what has been typical from other TGEs this year.
  • Lastly, the Hyperliquid team has not profited off of any of the trading activity on the platform. Fees are either burned or fully directed to HLP contributors and external market makers. Compensation would likely come through the form of a vesting team token allocation. This means that team incentives are fully aligned with the long term health of the protocol and asset, instead of short term vanity metrics.

Methods to Gain Exposure

There are currently three main methods to gain exposure to Hyperliquid:

  1. Depositing USDC into the HLP Vault
  2. Farming points
  3. Trading spot tokens

Viability of Each Method

Hyperliquid has built out user vaults, with its principal HLP vault carrying out an active market making strategy, collecting fees, and earning off perp DEX liquidations for passive USDC depositors. HLP’s 25%+ APR has attracted over $150 million in TVL as of July 24th, 2024. While increased trading activity over time on the perp DEX would likely lead to growth in HLP profits in aggregate, the vault has seen its APRs decrease steadily throughout the year as external market makers and new HLP depositors have diluted returns. This makes it hard to capture any significant value from Hyperliquid’s success through the vault method.

Secondly, as mentioned above, farming Hyperliquid points has become increasingly difficult. In order to maximize yields, one would need to have a highly active strategy which limits the return on effort for this method.

This leaves us with the spot market, which has several tailwinds going into the TGE.

The Case for Spot

We feel the best method to gain early exposure to Hyperliquid is to closely monitor the spot market for investable opportunities.

As of writing, Hyperliquid’s spot TVL pales in comparison to its perp TVL. With USDC TVL of only ~$20 million in spot, representing just 4.65% of total TVL, spot adoption is in its infancy. As Hyperliquid is able to offer native USDC post-EVM integration, inflows should pick up as simpler bridging and more reliable stablecoin availability comes about. We believe it is still early days for Hyperliquid spot.

Also of note, new spot deployments on Hyperliquid originate from a permissionless Dutch auction that takes place every 31 hours. This means only 282 new token listings can be created through the auction every year. This design could be beneficial because:

  • There is less competition for capital, as opposed to high deployment environments like Solana where thousands of new listings every day cannibalize volume.
  • Having to auction for deployment could filter out lower quality teams who are looking for a quick cash grab.
  • Spot deployment is still permissionless, unlike on CEXs where the criteria for listing is strict. This creates opportunities to invest in “early-stage” assets, whereas CEX listings usually occur after tokens are already fairly sizable.

Additionally, individual token liquidity cannot be pulled due to”Hyperliquidity”, a Hyperliquid invention that takes inspiration from Uniswap’s AMM model to offer native concentrated liquidity. This is enabled by Hyperliquid’s order book and matching engine, and does not require (although can be bolstered by) external market makers. Hyperliquidity creates an “un-ruggable” trading environment where bad actors can only rely on easily trackable token distribution manipulation to extort buyers.

Finally, holding spot tokens does provide some points, which essentially acts as a source of additional yield for the duration of the points program.

In summary, if investors are betting on Hyperliquid’s ability to grow its entire ecosystem, finding the right winners in an underpenetrated spot market could be the preferred method before the official Hyperliquid token is live. Favorable trading dynamics like scarce deployments and native liquidity are key value-adds.

What are Points Worth?

At ~$5 a point on Whales Market, the market could be coming in too conservative on the value of points. This may be because:

  • The Hyperliquid token’s expected fully diluted valuation (FDV) is still being indexed to more limited DeFi platforms such as other perp DEXs instead of to more comparable protocols like other Layer-1s and even $BNB.
  • Airdrop allocation estimates are reflecting other airdrops that had pre-TGE private rounds, large teams and thus, less supply to distribute.
  • The market may still be pricing in unplanned future dilution after the first season was extended without prior notice in May. However, with more nodes being added, a staking asset will surely be needed soon.

Given its new narrative, Hyperliquid should be valued at a premium over other perp DEX tokens like native $DYDX which has traded above $1 billion FDV since launch. The bull case would be Hyperliquid indexing to $BNB’s market cap which currently sits at ~$85 billion. Given that Hyperliquid’s most recent monthly volumes equate to ~6% of Binance’s, using an equivalent multiple would give us a FDV of ~$5 billion. However, BNB is one of the largest and most used EVM chains, so we only use this proxy as an upper bound and see Hyperliquid trading somewhere between dYdX and an early stage BNB.

We added up to ~51.1 million points expected to be distributed from the alpha season to the end of the current season. By plugging that result into some variable assumptions, we arrive at a wide range of potential outcomes:

We highlight some potential scenarios that output valuation results between $10 - $30 a point, posing significant upside to current expectations if no further points are distributed. A $2-4 billion dollar FDV would value Hyperliquid closer to L1 peers like Sei, and we believe 25-40% allocation towards points holders is in play given the supply dynamics discussed in earlier sections.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the market may be viewing Hyperliquid with an outdated framework. The performant L1 and incoming EVM compatibility will set it apart from the single use case DeFi applications or app-chains that Hyperliquid is currently being compared to. Instead, Hyperliquid’s bull case likely looks more like a fully onchain and permissionless Binance and BNB. Additionally, Hyperliquid’s native composable order book allows for a new suite of synergistic third party apps which could make the L1 a go-to destination for advanced trading, leverage, and other DeFi use cases.

Misguided narratives are leading to a mispricing of Hyperliquid points on OTC exchanges, and a re-rating could be in store as the team continues to build out more features. For those looking to participate in Hyperliquid’s growth story, the recently launched spot market has some runway to offer.
